---
// Standalone page for the desktop (Tauri) app: what it is, download, install
// walkthrough, import-format docs (mirrored from the app's own import dialog),
// annotations/data, FAQ. Unlinked from the rest of the site until a release
// exists — see app/src/pages/support.astro for the pattern this follows.
import ThemeInit from '../components/ThemeInit.astro';
import ThemeToggle from '../components/ThemeToggle.astro';
import '@shared/styles/global.css';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
const pageTitle = 'Desktop app — The Plato Reader';
const metaDescription =
  'The Plato Reader, offline: the same Greek text, public-domain ' +
  'translations, dictionary lookups, and Bekker-aligned search, in a free ' +
  'desktop app for macOS. Nothing you read or annotate leaves your computer.';
const canonical = Astro.site
  ? new URL(`${base}/desktop/`, Astro.site).href : undefined;
---
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <ThemeInit />
  <title>{pageTitle}</title>
  <meta name="description" content={metaDescription} />
  {canonical && <link rel="canonical" href={canonical} />}
  <meta property="og:type" content="website" />
  <meta property="og:title" content={pageTitle} />
  <meta property="og:description" content={metaDescription} />
  {canonical && <meta property="og:url" content={canonical} />}
  <meta property="og:site_name" content="The Plato Reader" />
  <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary" />
  <link rel="icon" href={`${base}/favicon.svg`} type="image/svg+xml" />
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" />
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin />
  <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Cardo:ital@0;1&family=EB+Garamond:ital,wght@0,400;0,600;1,400&display=swap" rel="stylesheet" />
  <style>
    .dt-body { max-width: 680px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 3rem 1rem 5rem; font-family: var(--font-english); color: var(--text); }
    .dt-eyebrow {
      font-family: var(--font-ui); font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: 600;
      letter-spacing: .12em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text-light);
      margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
    }
    .dt-body h1 { font-family: var(--font-english); font-weight: 600; font-size: 2rem; line-height: 1.15; margin: 0 0 1rem; }
    .dt-lede { font-size: 1.12rem; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0 0 1.1rem; color: var(--text); }
    .dt-body h2 {
      font-family: var(--font-ui); font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 600;
      color: var(--accent); margin: 2.4rem 0 0.7rem; letter-spacing: .02em;
    }
    .dt-body p { font-size: 1rem; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--text-mid); margin: 0 0 1.1rem; }
    .dt-body ul, .dt-body ol { margin: 0 0 1.1rem; padding-left: 1.3rem; color: var(--text-mid); }
    .dt-body li { font-size: 1rem; line-height: 1.65; margin: 0 0 0.5rem; }
    .dt-body li > strong { color: var(--text); }
    .dt-body a { color: var(--accent); }
    .dt-body code {
      font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, "SF Mono", Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
      font-size: 0.9em;
      background: var(--border);
      border-radius: 3px;
      padding: 0.05em 0.35em;
      color: var(--text);
    }
    .dt-body pre {
      font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, "SF Mono", Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
      font-size: 0.88rem;
      line-height: 1.6;
      background: var(--col-bg);
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: 6px;
      padding: 0.9rem 1.1rem;
      margin: 0 0 1.2rem;
      overflow-x: auto;
      color: var(--text);
    }
    .dt-cta {
      display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; align-items: baseline; gap: 0.75rem;
      margin: 1.4rem 0 0.5rem;
    }
    .btn-download {
      display: inline-block;
      font-family: var(--font-ui);
      font-size: .9rem;
      font-weight: 600;
      letter-spacing: .02em;
      text-decoration: none;
      padding: .6rem 1.2rem;
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: 4px;
      background: var(--border);
      color: var(--text-light);
      cursor: default;
    }
    .dt-version { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-light); }
    .dt-note { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-light); margin: 0.9rem 0 1.1rem; }
    .dt-note a { color: var(--accent); }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <header class="simple-header">
    <div class="header-title">
      <a class="home-link" href={`${base}/`}>Aristotle</a>
      <span class="title-sep">›</span>
      <span class="header-static">Desktop app</span>
    </div>
    <nav class="header-actions" aria-label="Navigation">
      <a href={`${base}/`} class="search-link">All works</a>
      <a href={`${base}/search`} class="search-link">Search</a>
      <ThemeToggle />
    </nav>
  </header>

  <main class="dt-body">
    <p class="dt-eyebrow">Desktop app</p>
    <h1>The Plato Reader — Desktop</h1>
    <p class="dt-lede">
      The Plato Reader is free online — this is the same reader, off the
      grid. The desktop app carries the whole public-domain corpus with it:
      Greek text and public-domain English translations, aligned line-for-line
      to the Bekker edition, dictionary lookups, and search, all built in.
    </p>
    <p>
      No connection required once it's installed, nothing loads from a
      server, and nothing you do in it — reading, importing, annotating — is
      sent anywhere. It's the same texts and the same alignment as the
      website, just private and offline.
    </p>

    <h2>Download</h2>
    <!-- TODO: DOWNLOAD_URL_TBD — wire up the real .dmg URL once the first
         release is built and the macOS minimum version / architecture
         coverage is confirmed (see src-tauri bundle config). -->
    <div class="dt-cta">
      <span class="btn-download" aria-disabled="true">Download for macOS</span>
      <span class="dt-version">version 0.2.0</span>
    </div>
    <p class="dt-note">Download link coming with the first release.</p>
    <p>
      Built for Macs on Apple silicon and Intel. (Minimum macOS version to be
      confirmed before this page goes live.)
    </p>
    <p>Windows and Linux builds aren't available yet — see the FAQ below.</p>

    <h2>Installing</h2>
    <p>
      The app isn't signed with an Apple Developer certificate, so the first
      time you open it, macOS Gatekeeper will step in and refuse a normal
      double-click. This doesn't mean anything is wrong — it's what Gatekeeper
      does for any app distributed outside the App Store without a paid
      developer certificate. The app is open source, so you can read exactly
      what it does.
    </p>
    <p>To open it the first time:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Download the <code>.dmg</code> and drag <strong>The Plato Reader</strong> into your Applications folder.</li>
      <li>In Applications, <strong>right-click</strong> (or Control-click) the app and choose <strong>Open</strong>.</li>
      <li>A dialog will ask if you're sure — click <strong>Open</strong>.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>After that first time, it opens normally, like any other app.</p>

    <h2>Importing your own translations</h2>
    <p>
      You're not limited to the built-in corpus. The app can import a
      plain-text or Markdown file of your own translation and align it to the
      Bekker spine automatically.
    </p>
    <p>
      Tags go in braces, placed immediately before the word they belong to
      (tag, one space, then the word). Use the numbers as printed in your
      source — never a computed count.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong><code>{'{1.7}'}</code></strong> — Chapter (book.chapter). Required, before the first word of each chapter. For single-book works, use book 1: <code>{'{1.4}'}</code> means chapter 4.</li>
      <li><strong><code>{'{1094a}'}</code></strong> — Bekker column. Optional, before the first word of that column.</li>
      <li><strong><code>{'{20}'}</code></strong> — Bekker line, within the current column. Optional, if your edition prints line numbers (usually every fifth line).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Example:</p>
    <pre>{'{1.1} Every art and every inquiry, and similarly\nevery action and pursuit, is thought to aim at\nsome good… {1094b} But a certain difference is\nfound among ends…'}</pre>
    <p>
      Whatever detail your tags don't provide is filled in by alignment — and
      always labelled as an estimate in the margin. Chapter tags alone are
      enough for a working parallel text; column and line tags simply sharpen
      it. The app also catches OCR line-break hyphens (like <code>under-</code>
      at the end of a scanned line) and asks you to confirm the ones it can't
      resolve on its own. You never write a metadata header by hand — the
      import form handles that.
    </p>
    <p>
      When you import, you're asked whether the file is a personal copy of a
      copyrighted translation. If so, it's kept private to your computer,
      never bundled or shared. If it's public domain or openly licensed, you
      can say so instead.
    </p>

    <h2>Annotations &amp; data</h2>
    <p>
      Everything you do in the app — highlights, notes, imported
      translations — is stored as plain files on your own machine, under your
      user Application Support folder
      (<code>~/Library/Application Support/org.platoreader.desktop/</code>
      on macOS). Annotations are one JSON file per work, shaped after the W3C
      Web Annotation model — an open, documented format, not a proprietary
      database. You can export a bundle of your annotations and imports at
      any time from the library panel, as a single file you can back up or
      move to another machine.
    </p>

    <h2>FAQ</h2>
    <p><strong>Is it free?</strong><br />
      Yes. Same as the website — no account, no paywall, no ads.</p>
    <p><strong>Does it phone home?</strong><br />
      No. The app doesn't make network requests in normal use. Nothing you
      read, import, or annotate leaves your computer. (Auto-update isn't
      wired up yet in this release; when it is, checking for updates will be
      the one exception, and it will be clearly optional.)</p>
    <p><strong>Is there a Windows or Linux version?</strong><br />
      Not yet. macOS is first because that's what the app is built and tested
      on; other platforms are possible later but aren't planned for a
      specific date.</p>
  </main>
</body>
</html>
